THE COMPLAINT

On Tuesday 21 September 2021 at approximately 08:59 UTC, I attended the NatWest
branch on Brixton Road — adjacent to my home address — to withdraw cash from my
own account. I presented my passport as identification. I have held an account
with NatWest since I was a child. This was my local branch.

1. REFUSAL OF SERVICE

The branch manager refused my withdrawal. I had valid government-issued
photographic identification. I was a lifelong customer at my home branch. No
lawful reason for the refusal has ever been communicated to me. I was angry at
being refused my own money. I did not threaten anyone. I recorded the
interaction on my phone. I have the video.

2. FALSE POLICE REPORT

I left the branch. On my way out I stopped and spoke with a female member of
staff downstairs. She was not threatened by me. I then went home — next door. I
started making breakfast.

After I had left the premises — after the situation was over, after I was no
longer present — NatWest staff called 999.

Metropolitan Police officers were at my door within five minutes.

No crime had been committed. No threat had been made. I had left the premises
voluntarily. The 999 call was made about a man who was no longer there, in
respect of an incident that was not a crime. The call wasted police resources
and subjected me to a priority police attendance at my home for the offence of
being angry at a bank.

I have video evidence of the interaction. The Metropolitan Police have been
asked to provide the 999 call recording via Subject Access Request. The
comparison between what actually happened (on video) and what NatWest told the
999 operator will speak for itself.

Full background, video evidence, transcript, and stills are published at:
https://github.com/roundtable-love/natwest


BREACH OF OBLIGATIONS

I believe NatWest's conduct on 21 September 2021 breached the following
obligations:

- FCA Principle 6 (Treating Customers Fairly): A lifelong customer was refused
  access to his own money with valid ID, at his home branch, for no communicated
  reason.

- FCA Principle 3 (Management and Control): The branch manager's decision to
  call 999 after I had left the premises suggests a failure of management
  judgement. The situation was over. There was nothing to report.

- Duty of care: NatWest owed me a duty of care as a customer. Calling 999 and
  making a report to police about me — after I had left — caused Metropolitan
  Police officers to attend my home. This was distressing and unnecessary.

- Data protection: NatWest disclosed my personal information to the Metropolitan
  Police via the 999 call without lawful basis. No crime had been committed. No
  ongoing threat existed. The disclosure was not necessary for any legitimate
  purpose.

- Data shared with debt collection agencies: NatWest has referred my account to
  debt collection agencies. I require disclosure of all information provided to
  those agencies about me, including any reference to the incident on 21
  September 2021 or any characterisation of me that originated from that
  incident.


WHAT I WANT

1. A written explanation of why my withdrawal was refused on 21 September 2021,
including the name and role of the person who made the decision.

2. A written explanation of why 999 was called after I had left the premises,
including who made or authorised the call and what was reported to police.

3. A copy of the 999 call recording, or confirmation that NatWest will cooperate
with the Metropolitan Police in providing it.

4. A copy of any incident report, security log, or internal record created in
connection with the incident.

5. A written apology for the refusal of service and the false police report.

6. Confirmation of what information was provided to any debt collection agency
about me, and whether any reference was made to the incident on 21 September
2021.

7. Compensation for distress caused by the unnecessary police attendance at my
home and the associated data protection breach.


